text: Just saw a private screening (no I don't work for the studio). The film is excellent and Chadwick Boseman gives a legendary performance on par with Bette Middler in "The Rose," Val Kilmer in "The Doors," and Diana Ross in "Lady Sings The Blues." He IS James Brown. Yes, there are small insights into his spousal and drug abuse, but the film really focuses on his musicianship and his influence on the African American community. The opening monologue alone by an older James Brown is pretty damn funny, and yes, the film itself is VERY funny, and knows when it's time to get serious.  The musical numbers are flawless, locales within each decade spot-on, and every supporting turn, small part, and extra blend in nicely. Dan Aykroyd goes back to his acting roots in "Driving Miss Daisy" with a nice supporting turn as Brown's manager. Viola and Octavia, great as always, and other standouts include Lennis James and Nelsan Ellis.  The film pulls no punches compared to the trailer which is a glossy veneer. The trailer will definitely draw crowds, but the film itself is a much darker and funnier then what's playing right now. And pays an excellent homage to James Brown.

text: The acting was SUPERB, but the writing SUCKED!!!  James Brown "always" talked proudly of his father with a lot of reverence and respect, but the writers chose to make his father look like an ignorant, abusive drunk.  Ever heard the song, "PAPA DON'T TAKE NO MESS"? Listen to it. This is what he wrote about is father: "Papa didn't cuss, he didn't raise a whole lot of fuss, but when we did wrong Papa beat the hell out of us" /  "I saw Papa cry when he thought that I would die, he said something was in his eye, but I knew it was a lie" / "Mama said, Papa's smart, Papa's got a whole lotta heart, said Papa would do his part, when the game get hard" / "Papa is a man who can understand, that a man has to do whatever he can" /  "Papa was a man who would take a stand" / "When Papa knows he's right, you got yourself a fight" / "Papa digs a chick if she looks real slick, Papa's rap is very quick, he definitely ain't no trick" ...  NONE OF THIS sounds like the guy that they "wrote" into the move.  Shame that the writers couldn't just keep it real.  I'm sure he hit is lady if she got out of hand...we now know that it's unacceptable... but most men did it back in the day whether they admit it or not...well, maybe not Ward Cleaver, but, he was a "TV dad...and none of that B.S. was even close to being real.
